<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[869,1494,1562,2131]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<bibRefCitation author="Wagler, J. G." box="[907,1084,1562,1587]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="469 - 750" refId="ref7165" refString="Wagler, J. G. 1832. Monographia psittacorum. Abhandlungen der Mathematisch-Physikalischen Klasse der Koniglich Bayerischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, 1: 469 - 750." type="journal article" year="1832">Wagler’s (1832)</bibRefCitation>
name 
<taxonomicName box="[1176,1310,1562,1587]" class="Aves" family="Psittacidae" genus="Ara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psittaciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caninde">
<emphasis box="[1176,1310,1562,1587]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Ara caninde</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Azara, F. de" box="[869,1027,1594,1619]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="ref5372" refString="Azara, F. de. 1805. Apuntamientos para la historia natural de los paxaros del Paraguay y Rio de la Plata. Madrid, Imprenta de la Viuda de Barra. v. 2." type="book" year="1805">Azara’s (1805)</bibRefCitation>
description of his Guacamayo caninde. This was for a long time thought to apply to the Bolivian endemic Blue-throated Macaw 
<emphasis box="[1281,1494,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dabbene" authorityYear="1921" box="[1281,1490,1658,1683]" class="Aves" family="Psittacidae" genus="Ara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psittaciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glaucogularis">Ara glaucogularis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, the identity was confirmed as this species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bertoni, A. de" box="[869,1031,1722,1747]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="39 - 40" refId="ref5464" refString="Bertoni, A. de W. 1922. Errores sobre el Caninde de Azara. Revista de la Sociedad Cientifica del Paraguay, 1 (3): 39 - 40." type="journal article" year="1922">Bertoni (1922)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Dabbene, R." box="[1093,1271,1722,1747]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="56" refId="ref5884" refString="Dabbene, R. 1920. El &quot; Caninde &quot; de Azara es el Ara ararauna (Lin.). El Hornero, 2: 56." type="journal article" year="1920">Dabbene (1920</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dabbene, R." box="[1284,1340,1722,1747]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="225" refId="ref5912" refString="Dabbene, R. 1921. Algunas palabras mas sobre el cambio de nombre del Ara caninde auct. El Hornero, 2: 225." type="journal article" year="1921">1921</bibRefCitation>
) with further clarification provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ingels, J." box="[1143,1343,1754,1779]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="283 - 294" refId="ref6105" refString="Ingels, J.; Parkes, K. C. &amp; Farrand Jr., J. 1981. The status of the macaw generally but incorrectly called Ara caninde (Wagler). Le Gerfaut, 71: 283 - 294." type="journal article" year="1981">
Ingels 
<emphasis box="[1215,1266,1754,1779]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
(1981)
</bibRefCitation>
. It seems that all Paraguayan reports can be traced back to this confusion. Two supposed Paraguayan specimens in the NHM mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Forshaw, J. F." box="[1032,1200,1850,1875]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="ref5983" refString="Forshaw, J. F. 1973. Parrots of the world. Melbourne, Lansdowne Press." type="book" year="1973">Forshaw (1973)</bibRefCitation>
are in fact from elsewhere (
<bibRefCitation author="Ingels, J." box="[875,1069,1882,1907]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="283 - 294" refId="ref6105" refString="Ingels, J.; Parkes, K. C. &amp; Farrand Jr., J. 1981. The status of the macaw generally but incorrectly called Ara caninde (Wagler). Le Gerfaut, 71: 283 - 294." type="journal article" year="1981">
Ingels 
<emphasis box="[949,1006,1882,1907]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">et al.,</emphasis>
1981
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[869,1494,1562,2131]" lastBlockId="7.[94,719,216,467]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<bibRefCitation author="Podtiaguin, B." box="[907,1109,1914,1939]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="7 - 120" refId="ref6639" refString="Podtiaguin, B. 1944. Catalogo sistematico de las aves del Paraguay. Aumentado por las contribuciones al conocimiento de la ornitologia paraguaya. Revista de la Sociedad Cientifica del Paraguay, 6 (3): 7 - 120." type="journal article" year="1944">Podtiaguin (1944)</bibRefCitation>
writes of a pair of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dabbene" authorityYear="1921" class="Aves" family="Psittacidae" genus="Ara" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psittaciformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="glaucogularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Ara glaucogularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being killed in Colonia Esperanza (probably Guairá department) on 
<date box="[1059,1213,1978,2003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1939-06-18">18 June 1939</date>
by E. Ávila (though earlier in the same publication he attributes the record to “E. Krenitsky”), with another taken by P. Willim at Colonia Nueva 
<collectingCountry box="[946,1002,2074,2099]" name="Italy" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Italia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1010,1231,2074,2099]" country="Paraguay" name="Central" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Central department</collectingRegion>
.The location of Colonia Esperanza is uncertain, as there is also a locality with this name in 
<collectingRegion box="[198,535,218,243]" country="Paraguay" name="Presidente Hayes" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Presidente Hayes department</collectingRegion>
(
<geoCoordinate box="[550,712,216,243]" degrees="23" direction="south" minutes="58" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" precision="1" seconds="04.36" value="-23.967878">
S 23°58 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[638,643,216,242]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">′</emphasis>
04.36 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[703,712,216,242]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">″</emphasis>
</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[94,263,248,275]" degrees="58" direction="west" minutes="45" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" precision="1" seconds="42.58" value="-58.76183">
W 58°45 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,194,248,274]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">′</emphasis>
42.58 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[254,263,248,274]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">″</emphasis>
</geoCoordinate>
). He describes the species as “travelling a lot” in certain years and it “not being rare to find it in 
<collectingCountry box="[94,198,314,339]" name="Paraguay" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
”. However, this is completely at odds with all available evidence, and as Podtiaguin had a tendency to write secondhand accounts of birds in a firsthand manner (Smith, 2016), it is far from clear whether he ever examined the specimens he wrote about.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
